  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a criminal offense in most jurisdictions worldwide. It is typically addressed under criminal legislation and is often part of anti-money laundering (AML) laws. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Legal Classification\n- Classified as a serious financial crime\n- Involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Considered a criminal offense with potential criminal penalties\n\n2. Typical Legal Consequences\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal record\n\n3. International Legislative Framework\n- Most countries have specific anti-money laundering statutes\n- United Nations and Financial Action Task Force (FATF) provide global guidelines\n- Legislation aims to prevent criminal proceeds from entering legitimate financial systems\n\n4. Common Criminal Provisions\n- Criminalizing money laundering activities\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing legal mechanisms for investigating and prosecuting offenses\n\n5. Jurisdictional Coverage\n- Applies to domestic and international financial transactions\n- Often covers various predicate criminal activities\n\nMoney laundering is universally treated as a serious criminal offense with comprehensive legal frameworks designed to detect, prevent, and punish such activities.",
